The rule covers GHG emissions from onshore petroleum and natural gas production, gathering and boosting, natural gas processing, and natural gas transmission compression facilities. It defines a facility as all equipment on a single well-pad or associated with a single well-pad, including leased, rented, or contracted activities, under common ownership or control, and located in a single hydrocarbon basin. The rule also specifies reporting requirements for different types of facilities, such as the quantities and types of emissions to be reported, the calculation methods to be used, and the conditions for reporting specific equipment or activities. It also outlines specific emission sources and components, such as natural gas dehydrators, compressors, generators, storage vessels, engines, boilers, heaters, and flares, and provides default emission factors for different equipment types. Additionally, it sets emission thresholds for reporting and specifies monitoring and QA/QC requirements for offshore petroleum and natural gas production facilities. The document also mentions the use of specific equations and default emission factors for calculating CO2, CH4, and N2O emissions from stationary or portable fuel combustion equipment at onshore petroleum and natural gas facilities.{
